<DIV class="govspeak">
<H2 id="overview">Overview</H2>
<P>This is for employers who would like to:</P>
<UL>
  <LI>understand the benefits of offering work experience</LI>
  <LI>find a suitable work experience programme</LI></UL>
<P>Work experience is an effective way of preparing young people and adults for 
employment. It can help to inform career choices, get people back into work, 
allow people to prove themselves to employers, and can help to instil the 
attitudes and behaviours expected at work.</P>
<P>Work experience includes a wide range of activities aimed at providing 
experience of the work environment. Placements can be either paid or unpaid, 
although some employers may choose to pay a wage even if not required to.</P>
<P>This guidance provides information about a range of government skills 
programmes that feature work experience or work placements, why employers might 
like to get involved and how to do so. We have also included useful resources 
about planning work experience placements, health and safety, supported 
internship placements and accreditation.</P>
<H2 id="benefits-of-offering-work-experience">Benefits of offering work 
experience</H2>
<P>Employers who offer work experience highlight these benefits:</P>
<UL>
  <LI><STRONG>recruitment</STRONG> – by identifying high-quality future recruits 
  and raising the profile of your business and sector. It also offers an 
  opportunity to get to know or ‘try out’ a potential employee before offering 
  them a job</LI>
  <LI><STRONG>staff development</STRONG> – by allowing your current staff to 
  develop and gain experience of supervision and people management skills</LI>
  <LI><STRONG>increased capacity</STRONG> – by filling temporary skills gaps or 
  vacancies, providing extra capacity or releasing current staff for other 
  work</LI>
  <LI><STRONG>new ideas and approaches</STRONG> – by bringing fresh energy and 
  motivation into your organisation, increasing the diversity of your workforce 
  and generating new ideas, approaches and ways of looking at the world</LI></UL>
<P>Aside from benefits to your organisation, there is also a strong social case. 
Offering work experience can give young people their first taste of a work 
environment. It can help to inform career choices and can help to instil the 
attitudes and behaviours expected at work. An extended period of unemployment 
can affect future employment prospects and lead to ill-health and poverty; work 
experience can help to prevent this, providing enormous benefits both to the 
individual and to the community.</P>
<H2 id="routes-for-work-experience">Routes for work experience</H2>
<H3 id="to-19-study-programmes-work-experiencehttpswwwgovukguidance16-to-19-funding-study-programmes-work-experience"><A 
href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/16-to-19-funding-study-programmes-work-experience">16 
to 19 study programmes: work experience</A></H3>
<P>Lasting from 2 to 8 weeks, work experience is a key component of study 
programmes for 16- to 19-year-olds on (predominantly) level 3 courses. 
Placements are arranged through training providers and funded by the Department 
for Education.</P>
<H3 id="careers-and-enterprise-company-careers-activitieshttpswwwcareersandenterprisecoukschool-activities"><A 
href="https://www.careersandenterprise.co.uk/school-activities" 
rel="external">Careers and Enterprise Company: careers activities</A></H3>
<P>Careers and Enterprise Company facilitates a wide range of employer and 
workplace activities for 11- to 18-year-olds, including work placements. 
Arranged by Enterprise Advisers drawn from the business community, activities 
can vary in length from a matter of hours to up to 2 weeks.</P>
<H3 id="work-experience-for-young-unemployed-jobseekershttpswwwgovukgovernmentpublicationsemployers-could-you-offer-work-experience"><A 
href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/employers-could-you-offer-work-experience">Work 
experience for young, unemployed jobseekers</A></H3>
<P>Jobcentre Plus organises standalone work placements for unemployed 18- to 
24-year-olds in receipt of benefits and some unemployed jobseekers aged 25 and 
over. Placements typically last from 2 to 8 weeks, and occasionally up to 3 
months.</P>
<H3 id="graduate-talent-pool-advertise-internshipshttpsgraduatetalentpoolsearchdirectgovukgtpinformation-for-employers"><A 
href="https://graduatetalentpoolsearch.direct.gov.uk/gtp/information-for-employers" 
rel="external">Graduate Talent Pool: advertise internships</A></H3>
<P>Graduate Talent Pool is a government website where employers can advertise 
graduate internship positions for free. Internships must be paid and can last 
for up to 12 months.</P>
<H3 id="sector-based-work-academieshttpswwwgovukgovernmentpublicationssector-based-work-academies-employer-guide"><A 
href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sector-based-work-academies-employer-guide">Sector-based 
work academies</A></H3>
<P>Sector-based work academies provide pre-employment training, work experience 
and a guaranteed job interview to unemployed benefit claimants of any age. 
Placements are arranged by Jobcentre Plus, typically last from 2 to 4 weeks and 
can help to meet employers’ recruitment needs.</P>
<H3 id="supported-internships-for-young-people-with-an-education-health-and-care-planhttpswwwgovukgovernmentpublicationssupported-internships-for-young-people-with-learning-difficulties"><A 
href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/supported-internships-for-young-people-with-learning-difficulties">Supported 
internships for young people with an education, health and care plan</A></H3>
<P>Supported internships are structured study programmes for 16- to 24-year-olds 
with special educational needs, based primarily at employers. Training providers 
arrange the unpaid work placement for 6 to 12 months.</P>
<H3 id="traineeshipshttpswwwgovukgovernmentcollectionstraineeships-programme"><A 
href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/traineeships-programme">Traineeships</A></H3>
<P>A traineeship is an education and training programme with work experience for 
16- to 24-year-olds with little to no experience of work. Training providers 
arrange these and they typically last from 3 to 6  weeks.</P>
<H3 id="t-level-industry-placementshttpswwwgovukgovernmentpublicationsintroduction-of-t-levelsintroduction-of-t-levelst-level-industry-placements"><A 
href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/introduction-of-t-levels/introduction-of-t-levels#T-Level-industry-placements">T 
level industry placements</A></H3>
<P>T levels are new 2-year, technical programmes designed with employers to give 
young people the skills that industry needs. Due to be rolled out in 2020, T 
levels will include an industry placement of at least 45 days in a learner’s 
chosen industry or occupation.</P>
<H3 id="work-and-health-programmehttpswwwgovukwork-health-programme"><A href="https://www.gov.uk/work-health-programme">Work 
and health programme</A></H3>
<P>The work and health programme provides personalised employment training and 
support to unemployed individuals who meet one of a wide range of eligibility 
criteria. Organised by Jobcentre Plus, support may include work placements or 
trials with potential employers.</P>
<H3 id="work-choicehttpswwwgovukwork-choice"><A href="https://www.gov.uk/work-choice">Work 
Choice</A></H3>
<P>Work Choice is a personalised employment training and support service for 
individuals with a disability or long-term health condition, featuring work 
placements if appropriate. Work Choice has now closed for new applicants.</P>
<H3 id="work-experience-for-school-pupils-reporthttpswwwgovukgovernmentpublicationswork-experience-and-related-activities-in-schools-and-colleges"><A 
href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/work-experience-and-related-activities-in-schools-and-colleges">Work 
experience for school pupils report</A></H3>
<P>Although no longer a statutory requirement, many schools arrange work 
placements with local employers for pupils aged 14 to 16. Placements typically 
last for 2 weeks.</P>
<H3 
id="work-trialshttpswwwgovukjobcentre-plus-help-for-recruiterswork-trials"><A 
href="https://www.gov.uk/jobcentre-plus-help-for-recruiters/work-trials">Work 
trials</A></H3>
<P>A work trial is a way of trying out a potential employee before offering them 
a job. Work trials are unpaid and can last for up to 30 days; they are for 
jobseekers of any age and are arranged through Jobcentre Plus.</P>
<H3 id="work-togetherhttpswwwgovukmoving-from-benefits-to-workwork-experience-and-volunteering"><A 
href="https://www.gov.uk/moving-from-benefits-to-work/work-experience-and-volunteering">Work 
Together</A></H3>
<P>The Work Together programme, arranged by Jobcentre Plus, enables unemployed 
jobseekers to volunteer with a local organisation.</P>
<H3 id="youth-obligationhttpswwwgovukguidancesupport-for-18-to-21-year-olds-claiming-universal-credit"><A 
href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/support-for-18-to-21-year-olds-claiming-universal-credit">Youth 
Obligation</A></H3>
<P>Youth Obligation is a programme of intensive support for 18- to 21-year-olds 
making a new claim to universal credit. Organised by Jobcentre Plus, it includes 
a guaranteed 3-month work placement for those still claiming after 6 months.</P>
<H2 id="further-information">Further information</H2>
<P>For employers wanting to find out more about setting up a work experience 
programme,</P>
<H3 id="general-guidance">General guidance</H3>
<P>The <A href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/employers-could-you-offer-work-experience">Department 
for Work and Pension’s employer guide</A> contains information relevant to 
providing work experience including induction, supporting participants, feedback 
and exit interviews, job search support, mentoring, buddying and shadowing.</P>
<P>UK Commission for Employment and Skills (now closed) gives advice on the 
employer’s role in work experience and how to provide a good quality work 
placement in ‘<A href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/work-experience-changes-to-government-policy">Making 
work experience work for you</A>’. Not ‘<A href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/not-just-making-tea-a-guide-to-work-experience">Just 
making tea</A>’ provides information on the importance of work experience and a 
range of case studies from employers who have successfully offered work 
placements.</P>
<P>Although primarily aimed at training providers, the department and 
Association of Colleges’ <A href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/post-16-work-experience-as-a-part-of-16-to-19-study-programmes">work 
experience readiness checklist</A> contains some relevant guidance for employers 
offering traineeships and other 16 to 19 study programme placements.</P>
<H3 id="pay-and-regulations">Pay and regulations</H3>
<P>Find out if you need to pay a <A href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/national-minimum-wage-work-experience-and-internships">minimum 
wage for work experience</A> placements, and  their <A href="https://www.gov.uk/employment-rights-for-interns">employment 
rights and pay</A>.</P>
<P>Employers are responsible for the <A href="http://www.hse.gov.uk/youngpeople/workexperience/placeprovide.htm" 
rel="external">health and safety of young people on work experience</A>.</P>
<H3 id="support">Support</H3>
<P>The <A href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/access-to-work-guide-for-employers">Access 
to Work guide</A> contains information about funding for employers who would 
like to offer internship placements to disabled people.</P>
<H3 id="quality-standard">Quality Standard</H3>
<P>Fair Train’s <A href="https://www.fairtrain.org/work-experience-quality-standard" 
rel="external">Work Experience Quality Standard</A> provides accredited, 
step-by-step guidance, with an associated kitemark, to help employers to provide 
a meaningful and quality work placement.</P>
<H3 id="other-information">Other information</H3>
<P>For sector-specific information, there are a wide range of guides produced by 
sector bodies and umbrella organisations, examples include:</P>
<UL>
  <LI>The Law Society’s <A href="http://www.lawsociety.org.uk/support-services/advice/articles/best-practice-guidance--work-experience-placements/" 
  rel="external">best practice guidance: work experience placements</A> </LI>
  <LI>CIPD’s <A href="https://www.cipd.co.uk/knowledge/fundamentals/people/routes-work/work-experience-guide" 
  rel="external">making work experience work: tips for employers</A> </LI>
  <LI>Go Construct’s <A href="https://www.goconstruct.org/inspire/information-for-employers/work-experience-information-for-employers/" 
  rel="external">work experience information for employers</A> 
</LI></UL></DIV></DIV>
