s a wide range of activities aimed at providing experience of the work environment. Placements can be either paid or unpaid, although some employers may choose to pay a wage even if not required to.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThis guidance provides information about a range of government skills programmes that feature work experience or work placements, why employers might like to get involved and how to do so. We have also included useful resources about planning work experience placements, health and safety, supported internship placements and accreditation.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2 id=\"benefits-of-offering-work-experience\"\u003eBenefits of offering work experience\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eEmployers who offer work experience highlight these benefits:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003e\n\u003cstrong\u003erecruitment\u003c/strong\u003e – by identifying high-quality future recruits and raising the profile of your business and sector. It also offers an opportunity to get to know or ‘try out’ a potential employee before offering them a job\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003e\n\u003cstrong\u003estaff development\u003c/strong\u003e – by allowing your current staff to develop and gain experience of supervision and people management skills\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003e\n\u003cstrong\u003eincreased capacity\u003c/strong\u003e – by filling temporary skills gaps or vacancies, providing extra capacity or releasing current staff for other work\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003e\n\u003cstrong\u003enew ideas and approaches\u003c/strong\u003e – by bringing fresh energy and motivation into your organisation, increasing the diversity of your workforce and generating new ideas, approaches and ways of looking at the world\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAside from benefits to your organisation, there is also a strong social case. Offering work experience can give young people their first taste of a work environment. It can help to inform career choices and can help to instil the attitudes and behaviours expected at work. An extended period of unemployment can affect future employment prospects and lead to ill-health and poverty; work experience can help to prevent this, providing enormous benefits both to the individual and to the community.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2 id=\"routes-for-work-experience\"\u003eRoutes for work experience\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"to-19-study-programmes-work-experiencehttpswwwgovukguidance16-to-19-funding-study-programmes-work-experience\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/guidance/16-to-19-funding-study-programmes-work-experience\"\u003e16 to 19 study programmes: work experience\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eLasting from 2 to 8 weeks, work experience is a key component of study programmes for 16- to 19-year-olds on (predominantly) level 3 courses. Placements are arranged through training providers and funded by the Department for Education.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"careers-and-enterprise-company-careers-activitieshttpswwwcareersandenterprisecoukschool-activities\"\u003e\u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.careersandenterprise.co.uk/school-activities\"\u003eCareers and Enterprise Company: careers activities\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCareers and Enterprise Company facilitates a wide range of employer and workplace activities for 11- to 18-year-olds, including work placements. Arranged by Enterprise Advisers drawn from the business community, activities can vary in length from a matter of hours to up to 2 weeks.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"work-experience-for-young-unemployed-jobseekershttpswwwgovukgovernmentpublicationsemployers-could-you-offer-work-experience\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/employers-could-you-offer-work-experience\"\u003eWork experience for young, unemployed jobseekers\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eJobcentre Plus organises standalone work placements for unemployed 18- to 24-year-olds in receipt of benefits and some unemployed jobseekers aged 25 and over. Placements typically last from 2 to 8 weeks, and occasionally up to 3 months.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"graduate-talent-pool-advertise-internshipshttpsgraduatetalentpoolsearchdirectgovukgtpinformation-for-employers\"\u003e\u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://graduatetalentpoolsearch.direct.gov.uk/gtp/information-for-employers\"\u003eGraduate Talent Pool: advertise internships\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eGraduate Talent Pool is a government website where employers can advertise graduate internship positions for free. Internships must be paid and can last for up to 12 months.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"sector-based-work-academieshttpswwwgovukgovernmentpublicationssector-based-work-academies-employer-guide\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sector-based-work-academies-employer-guide\"\u003eSector-based work academies\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSector-based work academies provide pre-employment training, work experience and a guaranteed job interview to unemployed benefit claimants of any age. Placements are arranged by Jobcentre Plus, typically last from 2 to 4 weeks and can help to meet employers’ recruitment needs.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"supported-internships-for-young-people-with-an-education-health-and-care-planhttpswwwgovukgovernmentpublicationssupported-internships-for-young-people-with-learning-difficulties\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/supported-internships-for-young-people-with-learning-difficulties\"\u003eSupported internships for young people with an education, health and care plan\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSupported internships are structured study programmes for 16- to 24-year-olds with special educational needs, based primarily at employers. Training providers arrange the unpaid work placement for 6 to 12 months.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"traineeshipshttpswwwgovukgovernmentcollectionstraineeships-programme\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/traineeships-programme\"\u003eTraineeships\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eA traineeship is an education and training programme with work experience for 16- to 24-year-olds with little to no experience of work. Training providers arrange these and they typically last from 3 to 6  weeks.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"t-level-industry-placementshttpswwwgovukgovernmentpublicationsintroduction-of-t-levelsintroduction-of-t-levelst-level-industry-placements\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/introduction-of-t-levels/introduction-of-t-levels#T-Level-industry-placements\"\u003eT level industry placements\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eT levels are new 2-year, technical programmes designed with employers to give young people the skills that industry needs. Due to be rolled out in 2020, T levels will include an industry placement of at least 45 days in a learner’s chosen industry or occupation.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"work-and-health-programmehttpswwwgovukwork-health-programme\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/work-health-programme\"\u003eWork and health programme\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe work and health programme provides personalised employment training and support to unemployed individuals who meet one of a wide range of eligibility criteria. Organised by Jobcentre Plus, support may include work placements or trials with potential employers.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"work-choicehttpswwwgovukwork-choice\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/work-choice\"\u003eWork Choice\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWork Choice is a personalised employment training and support service for individuals with a disability or long-term health condition, featuring work placements if appropriate. Work Choice has now closed for new applicants.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"work-experience-for-school-pupils-reporthttpswwwgovukgovernmentpublicationswork-experience-and-related-activities-in-schools-and-colleges\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/work-experience-and-related-activities-in-schools-and-colleges\"\u003eWork experience for school pupils report\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAlthough no longer a statutory requirement, many schools arrange work placements with local employers for pupils aged 14 to 16. Placements typically last for 2 weeks.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"work-trialshttpswwwgovukjobcentre-plus-help-for-recruiterswork-trials\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/jobcentre-plus-help-for-recruiters/work-trials\"\u003eWork trials\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eA work trial is a way of trying out a potential employee before offering them a job. Work trials are unpaid and can last for up to 30 days; they are for jobseekers of any age and are arranged through Jobcentre Plus.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"work-togetherhttpswwwgovukmoving-from-benefits-to-workwork-experience-and-volunteering\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/moving-from-benefits-to-work/work-experience-and-volunteering\"\u003eWork Together\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe Work Together programme, arranged by Jobcentre Plus, enables unemployed jobseekers to volunteer with a local organisation.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"youth-obligationhttpswwwgovukguidancesupport-for-18-to-21-year-olds-claiming-universal-credit\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/guidance/support-for-18-to-21-year-olds-claiming-universal-credit\"\u003eYouth Obligation\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYouth Obligation is a programme of intensive support for 18- to 21-year-olds making a new claim to universal credit. Organised by Jobcentre Plus, it includes a guaranteed 3-month work placement for those still claiming after 6 months.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2 id=\"further-information\"\u003eFurther information\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eFor employers wanting to find out more about setting up a work experience programme,\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"general-guidance\"\u003eGeneral guidance\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/employers-could-you-offer-work-experience\"\u003eDepartment for Work and Pension’s employer guide\u003c/a\u003e contains information relevant to providing work experience including induction, supporting participants, feedback and exit interviews, job search support, mentoring, buddying and shadowing.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eUK Commission for Employment and Skills (now closed) gives advice on the employer’s role in work experience and how to provide a good quality work placement in ‘\u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/work-experience-changes-to-government-policy\"\u003eMaking work experience work for you\u003c/a\u003e’. Not ‘\u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/not-just-making-tea-a-guide-to-work-experience\"\u003eJust making tea\u003c/a\u003e’ provides information on the importance of work experience and a range of case studies from employers who have successfully offered work placements.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAlthough primarily aimed at training providers, the department and Association of Colleges’ \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/post-16-work-experience-as-a-part-of-16-to-19-study-programmes\"\u003ework experience readiness checklist\u003c/a\u003e contains some relevant guidance for employers offering traineeships and other 16 to 19 study programme placements.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"pay-and-regulations\"\u003ePay and regulations\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFind out if you need to pay a \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/guidance/national-minimum-wage-work-experience-and-internships\"\u003eminimum wage for work experience\u003c/a\u003e placements, and  their \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/employment-rights-for-interns\"\u003eemployment rights and pay\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eEmployers are responsible for the \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.hse.gov.uk/youngpeople/workexperience/placeprovide.htm\"\u003ehealth and safety of young people on work experience\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"support\"\u003eSupport\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/access-to-work-guide-for-employers\"\u003eAccess to Work guide\u003c/a\u003e contains information about funding for employers who would like to offer internship placements to disabled people.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"quality-standard\"\u003eQuality Standard\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFair Train’s \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.fairtrain.org/work-experience-quality-standard\"\u003eWork Experience Quality Standard\u003c/a\u003e provides accredited, step-by-step guidance, with an associated kitemark, to help employers to provide a meaningful and quality work placement.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"other-information\"\u003eOther information\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor sector-specific information, there are a wide range of guides produced by sector bodies and umbrella organisations, examples include:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003eThe Law Society’s \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.lawsociety.org.uk/support-services/advice/articles/best-practice-guidance--work-experience-placements/\"\u003ebest practice guidance: work experience placements\u003c/a\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003eCIPD’s \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.cipd.co.uk/knowledge/fundamentals/people/routes-work/work-experience-guide\"\u003emaking work experience work: tips for employers\u003c/a\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003eGo Construct’s \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.goconstruct.org/inspire/information-for-employers/work-experience-information-for-employers/\"\u003ework experience information for employers\u003c/a\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003c/div\u003e"}
